<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900418-0172</DOCNO><DOCID>900418-0172.</DOCID><HL>   OECD Inflation Rate Slows</HL><DATE>04/18/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   EUROP</CO><LP>   PARIS -- A drop in energy prices and slower growth in foodcosts contributed to a decline in the monthly pace ofconsumer price growth in February for the 24 member nationsof the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development.   The organization said consumer prices rose 0.6% inFebruary, compared with a rise of 0.8% in January. But forthe 12 months through February, OECD consumer prices rose6.4%, higher than the 6.2% annual rate recorded in January.</LP><TEXT>   The OECD said a 0.2% decline in energy prices contributedto the slower February rise, after energy prices grew 1.9% onaverage in January. Food prices in February rose 0.9% fromJanuary, about half the rise reported in the previous month.Excluding food and energy prices, the underlying rate ofinflation in the OECD rose 0.5% in February from January,compared with 0.3% in January from December.</TEXT></DOC>